<p class="EnTeteTranscription">McKenzie, Charles. Journal of the Second, Third and Fourth Expeditions to the Missouri, 1805, 1806 with the Supplement to the Second Expedition. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0010</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">All the Traders who were in oppossition to me failing of success returned to the Red River and like me in the sole possession of the Mississouri Trade<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  I now divided my assortment into small parcels and made several Posts which I <span class="DelHand-author">put unto</span> placed under the charge of some of my men for the purpose of carrying on the <span class="DelHand-author">kindness to</span> business with the natives to the best advantages &#8211; and matters generally speaking did not fall far short of my expectations<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">When I was on the eve of my departure for Home The Black Cat one of the Chiefs, and with whom my men lodged in the Mandane village sent me word by an Indian to call at his Lodge as soon as possible &#8211; <span class="DelHand-author">Which</span> <span class="AddHand-author">which</span> <span class="DelHand-author"><span class="AddHand-author">this</span></span> I did immediately after<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  I <span class="DelHand-author">had</span> asked him the <span class="DelHand-author">nature</span> <span class="AddHand-author">cause</span> of <span class="DelHand-author">which should</span> this <span class="DelHand-author">such</span> peremptory invitation<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  My Son replied he, <span class="DelHand-author">Your men</span> <span class="AddHand-author">these people</span> do not mean to return with thee &#8211; they have disposed of their <span class="AddHand-author">own</span> property <span class="AddHand-author">in favor of</span> the Indians and would have taken thy property likewise <span class="AddHand-author">for the bad women</span> but I Knew they were bad White <span class="DelHand-author">people</span> <span class="AddHand-author">men</span> and have secured <span class="DelHand-author"><span class="Gap">[&#8230;]</span></span> <span class="AddHand-author">thy property that was theirs but</span> thine own<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  I applauded the Chief for his generous conduct then expressed a wish to cross over to the residence of <span class="DelHand-author">my</span> the bad White men to take them prisoners a<span class="AddHand-author">nd</span> <span class="DelHand-author">w<span class="Gap">[&#8230;]</span> to</span> have them punished<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  No Said the chief That will bring on a quarrel between me and the Indians in whose Lodges they are &#8211; for the Indians are bound to protect <span class="AddHand-author">such</span> strangers<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Seeing I could not do justice to my<span class="DelHand-author">self</span> <span class="AddHand-author">affairs</span> without causing disturbances I had all my property with the assistance of an Indian tra<span class="AddHand-author">n</span>sported to the upper villages<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Two days after I went down with Mor<span class="DelHand-author">r</span>ison to my deserted residence<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  When I entered the Lodge they seemed some what surprised<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="DelHand-author">I was</span> I tried to persuade them to return to their duty but I tried in vain &#8211; they would not yield obedience<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  I <span class="DelHand-author">therefore</span> was <span class="AddHand-author">therefore</span> obliged to leave</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">them</p>

<p align="page-number"><span class="AddHand-editors">[30]</span></p>

